 fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Camble","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campbel","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Cambell","meanings":["(1997: 229;2007: 1415; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campell","meanings":["(2007: 398; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and English: variant of   Campbell   (see also   Camel  )."]},{"name":"Beauchamp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."]},{"name":"Camel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Napoleon, Patrice.","English (of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Norman French <i>came(i)l</i> ‘camel’ (from Latin <i>camelus</i>, classical Greek <i>kamēlos</i>), possibly denoting a clumsy person or someone with long legs. It may also be a topographic or habitational name referring to a house with a sign depicting a camel (although surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English); compare 5 below.","English: possibly a habitational name from Queen Camel and West Camel in Somerset, early recorded as <i>Camel(le)</i>, possibly a Celtic name from <i>canto-</i> ‘border, district’ and <i>mēl</i> ‘bare hill’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Campbell was born in 1330, in Scotland, his father, Sir Dougal Campbell - Laird of Auchinbreck, was 18 and his mother, Mariot Margaret de Dundee, was 41. He married Mariota Campbell about 1345, in Argyll, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1380, in his hometown, at the age of 50, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"1330–1380":"1330–1380","1328–1357":"1328–1357","1345–1420":"1345–1420","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1312–1333":"1312–1333","1290–1340":"1290–1340","5 April 1357":"5. aprill 1357","before 1330":"enne 1330","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","1290":"1290","1357":"1357","1312":"1312","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1420":"1420","about 1345":"umbes 1345","January 1345":"jaanuar 1345","1328":"1328","Lochgoilhead, Argyll, Scotland":"Lochgoilhead, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland":"Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland"},"fi":{"1330–1380":"1330–1380","1328–1357":"1328–1357","1345–1420":"1345–1420","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1312–1333":"1312–1333","1290–1340":"1290–1340","5 April 1357":"5. huhtikuuta 1357","before 1330":"ennen vuotta 1330","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","1290":"1290","1357":"1357","1312":"1312","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1420":"1420","about 1345":"noin 1345","January 1345":"tammikuu 1345","1328":"1328","Lochgoilhead, Argyll, Scotland":"Lochgoilhead, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland":"Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland"},"fr":{"1330–1380":"1330–1380","1328–1357":"1328–1357","1345–1420":"1345–1420","1350–Male":"1350–Décéd